Date: Fri, 24 Mar 2000 09:41:05 -0500
From: Nina Jochnowitz <NJOCHNOWITZ@synapticcorp.com>

It is beyond me that people go to such lengths to capture Vampire bats,
smearing coagulant paste on there backs, so you can see which cattle are
bitten. Why not just inoculate them and notch there wings so you know which
ones are inoculated? It seems like such a waste to watch cattle which have
been fed upon by "coagulant treated bats" when you could certainly stop the
disease transmission by inoculating the carriers. Cost of loosing
livestock has definitely not been included in your "cost beneficial"
treatment of this problem.
--
Nina Jochnowitz
e-mail: NJOCHNOWITZ@synapticcorp.com
